Introduction

The purpose of this project is to lead a bayesian analysis dealing with the growth of the height of a population of Loblolly pine trees.

library(datasets)
library(R2jags)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggmcmc)
data("Loblolly")

Data analysis

The Loblolly data frame has 84 rows and 3 columns of records of the growth of Loblolly pine trees. The three columns are:

  • height: a numeric vector of tree heights (ft).
  • age: a numeric vector of tree ages (yr).
  • Seed: an ordered factor indicating the seed source for the tree. The ordering is according to increasing maximum height.

First of all i trasformed the original dataset into a new one. The new dataset is composed by 6 columns (the different ages at which the height was recorded) and 14 rows: the height tree by tree at the different ages.

loblolly.data <- list(x=c(3,5,10,15,20,25), x.bar=13, N=14, T = 6, Y=c(Loblolly$height))

Each trees height follows a linear growth. Due to similarity with the behavior of rats height study by Gelfand et al (1990), i decided to used rats example in Open Bugs for the building of the model.

Its important to analyze the frequentist approach in order to get more info on the parameters and to evaluate the difference between the two process. The frequentist estimate of the parameters could help us to determine the init values for the jags model. The approach was conceived by getting a mathematical linear equation that relates the features and the response variable. This was done by linear regression

Model 1

The model is essentially a random effects linear growth curve:

\[Y_{ij}\sim Norm(\mu_{ij},\tau_c)\] \[\mu_{ij}\sim\alpha_i+\beta_i(x_j-\bar{x})\] \[\tau_c\sim Gamma(0.001,0.001)\] \[\alpha_i\sim Norm(\alpha_c,\tau_{\alpha})\] \[\beta_i\sim Norm(\beta_c,\tau_{\beta})\] \[\alpha_c\sim Norm(0,10^{-6})\] \[\beta_c\sim Norm(0,10^{-6})\] \[\tau_{\alpha}\sim Gamma(0.001,0.001)\] \[\tau_{\beta}\sim Gamma(0.001,0.001)\]

where \(\tau\) represents the precision (1/variance) of a normal distribution. We standardise the \(x_j\)s around their mean to reduce dependence between \(\alpha_i\) and \(\beta_i\) in their likelihood: in fact for the full balanced data, complete independence is achieved. (Note that, in general, prior independence does not force the posterior distributions to be independent). \(\alpha_c\,,\beta_c\,,\tau_{\alpha}\,,\tau_{\beta}\,,\tau_c\) are non-informative priors.

model <- function()  {
  for (i in 1:N) {
    for (j in 1:T) {
      Y[i,j]   ~ dnorm(mu[i,j],tau.c) 
      mu[i,j] <- alpha[i] + beta[i]*(x[j]-x.bar);
    }
    
    alpha[i] ~ dnorm(alpha.c,tau.alpha);
    beta[i]  ~ dnorm(beta.c,tau.beta); }
    alpha.c   ~ dnorm(0,1.0E-6);
    beta.c    ~ dnorm(0,1.0E-6);
    tau.c     ~ dgamma(1.0E-3,1.0E-3);
    tau.alpha ~ dgamma(1.0E-3,1.0E-3);
    tau.beta  ~ dgamma(1.0E-3,1.0E-3);
    sigma <- 1.0 / sqrt(tau.c)
    x.bar    <- mean(x[]);
    alpha0 <- alpha.c - beta.c * x.bar
}

loblolly.data.list <- list('Y', 'x', 'T', 'N')

loblolly.inits <- function() {
  list(alpha=c( -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31, -1.31), 
       beta = c(2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6),
       alpha.c = 4.24, beta.c = 10,
       tau.c = 1, tau.alpha = 1, tau.beta=1) }

jags_model <- jags(data=loblolly.data.list, inits=loblolly.inits, loblolly.params, n.chains=3,  n.iter=10000,n.burnin=5000, n.thin=1, model.file=model, DIC=TRUE)

One way to see if our chain has converged is to see how well our chain is mixing, or moving around the parameter space. If our chain is taking a long time to move around the parameter space, then it will take longer to converge. We can see how well our chain is mixing through visual inspection. We need to do the inspections for every parameter.

results=ggs(jags_model.mcmc)

ggs_traceplot(results)

The traceplots show that the parameters converge to the theoretical distributions.

Model2

In this second model we want try to change some prior parameters and see what happen at our model. Our prior sigma.alpha and sigma.beta are distributed as uniform.

\[Y_{ij}\sim Norm(\mu_{ij},\tau_c)\] \[\mu_{ij}\sim\alpha_i+\beta_i(x_j-\bar{x})\] \[\tau_c= \frac{1}{\sigma^2}\] \[\sigma \sim Unif(0,100)\] \[\alpha_i\sim Norm(\alpha_c,\tau_{\alpha})\] \[\beta_i\sim Norm(\beta_c,\tau_{\beta})\] \[\alpha_c\sim Norm(0,10^{-6})\] \[\beta_c\sim Norm(0,10^{-6})\] \[\tau_{\alpha}=\frac{1}{\sigma^2_\alpha}\] \[\sigma^2_\alpha \sim Unif(0,100)\] \[\tau_{\beta}=\frac{1}{\sigma^2_\beta}\] \[\sigma^2_\beta \sim Unif(0,100)\]

model2 <- function()  {
  for (i in 1:N) {
    for (j in 1:T) {
      
      mu[i,j] <- alpha[i] + beta[i]*(x[j]-x.bar);
      Y[i,j]   ~ dnorm(mu[i,j],tau.c) 
      
    }
    
    alpha[i] ~ dnorm(alpha.c,tau.alpha);
    beta[i]  ~ dnorm(beta.c,tau.beta); }
  alpha.c   ~ dnorm(0,1.0E-6);
  beta.c    ~ dnorm(0,1.0E-6);
  tau.c     <- 1.0 / (sigma*sigma);
  sigma  ~ dunif(0,100)
  tau.alpha <- 1.0 / (sigma.alpha*sigma.alpha);
  sigma.alpha ~ dunif(0,100)
  tau.beta <- 1/(sigma.beta*sigma.beta)
  sigma.beta ~ dunif(0,100)
  x.bar    <- mean(x[]);
  alpha0 <- alpha.c - beta.c * x.bar
}
loblolly.params2 <- c("alpha.c", "beta.c", "sigma", "sigma.alpha", "sigma.beta")

       beta = c(2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6,2.6),
       alpha.c = 4.24, beta.c = 10,

Model comparison through DIC

Lets compare two model with the Deviance Information Criterion: this analyzes the models in terms of deviance. and is given by \(DIC = \overline{D} + p_D\) or \(DIC = \hat{D} + 2 * p_D\) . \(p_D\) : this is the effective number of parameters, and is given by \(pD = \overline{D}-\hat{D}\). Thus \(p_D\) is the posterior mean of the deviance minus the deviance of the posterior means. \(\hat{D}\) : this is a point estimate of the deviance (\(2log(L(\bar{\theta}))\)) obtained by substituting in the posterior means theta.ba r of thet a: thus \(\hat{D}= -2 * log(p(y|\overline{\theta}))\). \(\overline{D}\) : this is the posterior mean of the deviance, which is exactly the same as if the node deviance had been monitored. This deviance is defined as \(-2 * log(L)\): likelihood is defined as \(p(y|\theta)\), where y comprises all stochastic nodes given values (i.e.data), and thet a comprises the stochastic parent s of y - stochastic parents are the stochastic nodes upon which the distribution of y depends, when collapsing over all logical relationships.

The model with the smallest DIC is estimated to be the model that would best predict a replicate dataset of the same structure as that currently observed.

cat('DIC for 1st model: ', jags_model$BUGSoutput$DIC)
## DIC for 1st model:  433.8871
cat('DIC fro 2nd model: ', jags_model2$BUGSoutput$DIC)
## DIC fro 2nd model:  432.2262

Due to slower DICs value for the second model its possible say that this one works better than the first.
